A few fights: MP3 players versus cell phones.
We'll help you choose
While almost all cell phones can play MP3 files, you can't use any MP3 player to make a phone call.
It seems clear that it's better to just buy a phone.
Still, there are many reasons why you should get a separate MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the needs of the prospective owner.
You're probably having a hard time getting a high-end, expensive record player at home to play the latest Maxim Turbulence record.
On the one hand, such musical products do not appear on bakelite records, but there is no objective reason for this from a quality point of view.
But if you have a record store full of art rock, jazz, or blues, you probably dream of a record player like this.
It's similar to traveling, which is compressed - simplified to MP3 music.
There are price and quality categories here too.
It may be unacceptable for some to spend eight thousand kroner for a record player, just as a Pink Floyd fan may find it difficult to accept a 20-kr market-priced headset.
Two extremes, with enough room for everyone.
There's a lot to choose from.
The life of the batteries also matters
Some of the best music players are capable of doing more than just playing music, but also something that most mobile phones don't even have the chance to do.
No other device today is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to the basic functions of calling and texting, it can play music and video, record both, have a camera for both right and wrong, and even navigate.
And if you consider smartphones and communicators, he's got a little computer in his pocket.
It's a miracle, because no refrigerator can barbecue and no television can take pictures.
Multi-functional phones have their drawbacks.
The more functions you use on your phone, the more times the display sends you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy-consumers.
Few mobile devices can play music for more than 10 or 12 hours, but most of them are much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest) are significantly more powerful.
So, with cheap cell phones, you can expect them to be off your phone for a few hours.
If you are also on the phone, get a charger at work for safety reasons - even for more expensive devices.
MP3 players won't have that problem, and even the worst ones can handle at least nine hours of continuous playback on a single charge.
The next problem is when you're uploading music to your phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector and, moreover, not all of them can be connected directly to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but few card readers can handle the miniature memory cards used in mobile phones without an adapter.
With a few exceptions (iPod) the players don't need any special software.
You just need to load the device with music from the computer via USB.
Most mobile phones and players already have their own music library, sorted by performer, album, genre, or user rating.
Some devices only represent a string structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some can do both (i.e. iver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with an operating system).
Players are easier to handle, mobile phones are more capable
When choosing a particular device, consider the battery life, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output, and of course the comfort of handling.
If music is your primary background and you only listen to it for a short time each day, such as on the subway, any MP3 player phone is fine.
And that's what any phone can do.
You don't have to pay much attention to what music formats your phone or player can play.
They all deal with MP3s, and the vast majority of the music that you get is in that format.
MP3 is one of the most common and besides it the vast majority of devices also deal with music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and for its iPod) is less common.
Better mobile phones also enable online music purchases, for example.
All you have to do is visit the relevant website of the service provider (or other service provider) via the mobile internet and purchase the song or album.
This service alone can be a compelling argument for buying music on mobile.
Unfortunately, the service providers are a bit short-sighted and usually limited to one-year radio camps.
The prices aren't the lowest either.
However, it is generally assumed that this particular way of selling music (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their mobile devices with them all the time.
Whenever he wants to listen to something, he puts his phone in his pocket while his forgotten MP3 player lies at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry your headphones or at least your speakers.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker, which is available on almost all mobile phones, but only a few MP3 players have it.
For many, the biggest advantage of mobile music is probably the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
Between three and four thousand crowns, you can get a decent walkman.
But more often than not, you're limited by the lack of output from a conventional earphone.
The best and most technically equipped phones with conventional 3.5 mm diameter holes in the headphones can cost up to 15,000 kroner.
The advantage of the players, however, is that they are easy to use.
Everyone can handle the simplest - not necessarily the cheapest - players (see our selection).
Minimal function, the previously standard tape recorder and gramophone-like handling is obvious.
There is no threat of collapse in the form of accidentally switched on mobile internet and the huge bill for data transmission that follows.
What to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an opening for interchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
The maximum amount is 2,000 kroner, even if you buy the right card.
But be careful.
The basic types only support cards with a maximum capacity of up to 2 GB.
Only the most expensive can afford an 8GB memory card.
If you already have a mobile phone and you want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowboy, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgetton or Envy.
Based on capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than SEK 1100.
If you are a more demanding student, you may prefer to use a special mobile walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices also have a separate MP3 control button, making the control convenient to the MP3 player.
The industry's most advanced player is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman series of mobile phones have the same user interface as the MP3 players sold separately.
The MP3 players of the above brands can provide the same service at the same price category up to SEK 4000, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will be in the Czech Republic later this year.
Maybe I should.
The Czech mobile market is relatively developed and our operators offer virtually the same services as their Western European counterparts.
However, we are missing something here - a virtual service provider that forces the traditional providers to significantly reduce their prices.
Maybe it won't be that long.
We've written on Mobil.cz many times that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by the Czech authorities, which pointed out that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in other EU countries.
The latest move by the European Commission to regulate roaming charges may lead to a contradictory situation: some customers of Czech mobile operators will have cheaper SMS messages from abroad than domestic ones.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition to really fight.
Now, this may sound counterintuitive, because we have three cellular networks and we're at a very high penetration of over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
This is often agreed with Pavel Dvořák, the chairman of the Czech Telecommunications Board, who has stated several times before that there is no place for a new operator in the Czech Republic.
It may be true that the traditional operator with its own network probably has little chance (and therefore probably has difficulty finding frequencies).
But there is another option - the virtual service provider.
The entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant price reduction, to which the traditional operators have had to respond.
Meanwhile, even before big names like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile came on the market, voices like ours were heard in Britain.
However, it has been proven that such providers have a place and can indeed be successful.
Nevertheless, we don't have to go too far to give an example.
In February of this year, we informed you about the launch of Mobilking, a virtual service provider in Poland.
In less than six months, the operator managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual service providers is that they can focus on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate efficiently, it needs far fewer customers than a traditional provider.
It does not involve relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers in the world thus generally appear to be low-cost - offering cheap calls and text messages, which are often offset by less service.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers text messages at least 50 percent cheaper than its competitors.
But as Mobilking in Poland shows, it's a pretty good bet on a target audience.
This is a service that specifically targets men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - a service they like, one they can trust", says David Seibert, CEO of Mobil Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual service.
It is difficult to say whether a similar idea in Poland will work here.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesman for Vodafone, doubts this: 'The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it was relatively satisfactory in terms of the provision of services.'
In the Czech Republic, the mobile operators claim that
However, it seems almost certain that if there is any virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about a successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not seem very promising.
Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region", said Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for Penta Financial Group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
By implication, it showed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic were not overly sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they will do their utmost to avoid any potential competition.
The GTS Novera Group has been keen to launch the virtual service for some time now, and it intends to take another step forward in order to make Telefonica O2 a real competitor in the corporate customer space.
"We are very interested in providing our customers with not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
This possibility has been discussed repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in negotiations", says Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
Maybe better times are coming.
Unofficial information suggests we may have a chance to get the first virtual service provider by the end of the year.
But for now, his birth is surrounded by a wall of impenetrable silence.
'At the moment we do not think that a full-fledged virtual service provider has a place on the Czech market.
The Czech market is very special compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by a single entity offering complex and serious projects in this area", Vlastimil Sršeň, from the press department of Telefónica 02, told Mobil.cz.
The special situation of the Czech market is also cited by other operators.
Martina Kemrová, spokesperson for T-Mobile, agrees with O2 in an exceptional way and adds: 'We have not yet registered any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further.'
And he added, "T-Mobile's network is unlikely to have any virtual service providers until the end of the year.
A concrete agreement should be on the table at this moment to be able to think in such a short time".
Vodafone is focusing on meeting its own 3G licensing requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: 'We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
From the customer's point of view, we find that to be the most rewarding.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find partners to build shared networks for high-speed mobile internet.'
Responsible agencies - on a level playing field with service providers
The behaviour of mobile operators is easy to understand, and the entry of a new operator would increase competition, lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
So why facilitate such competition?
When the service providers are able to collaborate on something important, the story of the birth of U:fon is also witnessed.
The biggest pressure on the CTU was probably the birth of the U:fonte of T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by the publicly available information on the CTU website.
But right now, U:fon is a good argument for why we shouldn't allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrová added: 'The competitive environment in the mobile market has recently been affected by the entry of the fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of a new player into the market and its services will place high demands on it.'
However, given the attitude of mobile operators, the complete disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is quite astonishing.
In the meantime, it is not just the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately, unlike the UK and other developed countries, has no right to interfere in economic competition.
The Competition Authority is the sole authority.
But the Bureau has a very specific approach to the whole problem.
'The entry of a virtual service provider into the mobile market would only be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile service provider and the virtual service provider for the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contracts have been concluded so far, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently attractive to traditional operators,' said Kristián Chlapua, from the Competition Office's external relations department.
A statement from the representatives of the service providers in this way would probably not surprise anyone.
But this is more than strange from an agency which should represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensure that no one abuses its market position.
Alternatively, adds Kristián Chalupa: "Outside the EU, where virtual service providers are commonly active, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the decrease in the price of mobile phone services".
However, it is likely that pressure to maintain the proper functioning of the market environment and to reduce prices is not in the interests of ÚOHS.
The case is truly shocking, and the response of the three mobile operators is quite touching.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is almost self-evident.
Like gas stations, the exact same gas prices are probably just the result of chance and fierce competition.
'The Office has not detected any evidence of anti-competitive conduct in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
Neither of the operators has a leading position, i.e. no proportionate responsibility for its market activities.
The telecoms regulator is also likely to lack the tools needed to open up the mobile market for virtual service providers,' Chalupa said.
The presentation of the market leadership position is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTU, which shows that telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, there is of course no Czech operator in a leading position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the establishment of a virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator, relatively logically, has a monopoly on its own network.
So in a certain segment it's necessarily dominant.
But even if we did not accept this argument, it should be a minimum for the NRA to believe that three mobile operators behave in a remarkably similar way.
Meanwhile, the complaints of a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in the course of negotiations with all the operators.
The transfer of responsibility to the CCP is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, which takes the ÚOHS off the case.
We've seen this in a few similar situations.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted Telecommunications Act did not allow the extension of the competence of ČTU in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts hoped that this would improve the situation.
The representatives of the U.N. Security Council must know this, but they probably have other interests.
It works when no one's watching.
Meanwhile, the operation of some virtual service providers, of which there are already many operating on Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that publish their own mobile phone service price lists, which are only partially public.
Because these are multi-level marketing companies.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
These companies' price lists usually only get to the chosen few.
The magic is that the company is acting against the service provider like a classic corporate customer who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a preferred customer, it will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial terms of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar pre-emption.
'If there were cases of which you are talking, it could be a breach of contract that we would deal with and which could lead to the termination of cooperation with the company in question,' answered Martina Kemrová to our question on this problem.
But it's unlikely that news of such activity would not have reached the people in charge of the mobile operators.
In particular, the three companies mentioned above may have thousands of customers.
Meanwhile, no provider is defending itself against such a procedure.
These companies have a significant profit from their activities and, unlike real virtual service providers, are not particularly threatened by their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of the potential problems: "The law allows for such speculation, yet only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card is not in their name and therefore they cannot have it fully as a general customer of mobile operators.'
But that's what the CTU should be curious about.
In addition, another question arises for the OHIM.
If mobile operators are turning a blind eye to this kind of procedure, why are they preventing the birth of a virtual carrier?
It should be added that the OHIM has a relatively strong legal capacity to detect such activity and, if it does not wish to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation by the service providers that they did not suspect such activity and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're not the most expensive
As has been stated several times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a significant decrease in the price of services.
Meanwhile, in virtually all countries where virtual service providers have been established, traditional service providers have more or less tried to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were essentially the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But in developed countries, it was at this very moment that regulators intervened, not to protect the interests of mobile operators, but of their customers.
And then, either through formal measures or informal pressure, they got the first virtual service provider to follow.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are handing the whole thing over to each other.
In our experience, we cannot shake the impression that they are well-suited to having ambiguous competences in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is indeed coming soon, the Czech mobile market may be back on track.
If one of the providers were to allow the creation of a virtual mobile service, it would be difficult for the OHIM to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And compared to the rest of Europe, we may not be more expensive to call.
There are four new versions of the new Czech anthem.
Choose the Best
Listen to four takes of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem "Where is my country?" on the occasion of the Czech Republic's National Day.
The anthem was recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - male or female soloists, with vocal arm or instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka are singing.
The modification of the hymn was written by Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on the website iHNed.cz.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national anthem to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
Czech Radio has previously told that it has deliberately selected young singers with representative voices, expressive and popular, to sing solo variations.
"From the very beginning, I tried to be clear in my diction, clear in my lyrics, and harmonious in my work with both of them and later with the orchestra", he said.
The Czech national anthem is celebrating its 175th anniversary next year.
Where is my homeland? was first performed at the Rendi Theatre in 1834 in Josef Kajetán's Tyl Fidlovačka, with music by František Škroup.
It became popular, and people spontaneously adopted it.
The first verse of the song became a natural part of the national anthem after the establishment of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
After the establishment of the independent Czech Republic, it remained one of the seven state symbols.
