Prague Transportation Company will deliver for the first time on Wednesday with a chip card
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will go down in Prague Transport Company history as the date when the first passenger to board the subways, trams and buses will have an electronic ticket in his pocket instead of a paper ticket.
The coupon is currently available to approximately 100,000 Opencard chip card holders.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day and an annual coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time deposit it on their chip card at the information centres and booking offices of the Transport Company at the Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
Since yesterday, coupons can also be purchased online through the Transport Company's website www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than 400 customers by the afternoon.
Those who start using the Internet for business can forget about the ticket offices in the metro, where they have regularly had to wait in long lines for tickets.
The voucher can be purchased online and the Opencard card can be purchased at one of the thirteen counters of the City Library.
"These places offer passengers a desk with trained waiters who help them shop online and save their purchased vouchers on their card", said Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
In addition to libraries, e-vouchers for Opencard will also be available in the self-service machines in some lobbies.
What do these vending machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket officers, and passengers may have already noticed them at the Rozyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty", added Opatrný.
The coupon is checked by an automaton instead of the driver
Operating the automata that start tomorrow is simple.
All you have to do is insert the Opencard chip card and the previously paid coupon will automatically be forfeited.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area.
So on the trains and bus lines around the city from 300 to 499, which mainly travel to the capital by residents of the Central Czech routes.
"On the Prague integrated trains, the drivers were provided with card readers, which also help to determine the zone validity of the coupons", explained Filip Drápal of Ropid, the organisation that compiles the Prague public transport timetable.
On buses around town, card readers are installed at the driver's desk and the cash register.
The driver must therefore not only show the chip card when boarding but also place the Opencard in a specified place on the side of the cash register.
The driver checks the validity of the coupons.
"If a passenger needs to check the validity of coupons, for example, the easiest way is to ask the driver", Drápal added.
Passengers who travel on non-city buses and do not remember when their coupons expire can go back to the vending machines that save coupons on cards.
Information on the validity of their documents is displayed here on the display of the equipment.
The Swedes wanted a referendum on the United States.
The Sudeten Germans demanded the annexation of Šumava to the United States in 1945.
This is according to the letter in the collection of the South Czech Scientific Library.
If we can't be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
It is said that in 1945 a group of Sudeten Germans approached the President of the United States with this request.
This is also revealed by a letter from a private archive, now kept in the South Czech Scientific Library.
The Czechs in Krumlov ask the American president not to allow the return of the "Sumava County" to the Czech Republic, which Hitler had seized under the Munich Treaty.
"We have interpreted the situation correctly and we really want to be sure in the words that the American troops are not coming to German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", the letter reads, signed "People who bear the fate of Šumava in their hearts".
Since annexation of Czechoslovakia would supposedly give the Sudeten Germans - despite their knowledge of the Czech national character - only hope for brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the protectorate over Šumava "now and forever".
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of four million inhabitants, this territory would be considered a foreign country, which oppresses and exploits the minority and would contribute almost nothing to the victory of the Allies", the letter states.
The reason why the authors could not sign was supposedly fear of revenge from the "Czech oppressors".
So if the president of the United States supposedly doubted the opinion of the Germans in Shumava, it would be enough to hold a referendum in Shumava County on whether its people want to become part of the United States and live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may seem a bit naive in the light of modern knowledge of postwar history, some historians believe it adequately reflects the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
