Rats have feelings too.
If a rat or a moth is in danger, it will run away.
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that animals have feelings.
But how can we test whether they feel the same way when they behave in a way that we do?
The online magazine "Edge" has been publishing articles by renowned scientists for years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE has a series of articles on the question "What do you think is real without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have emotions and other states of consciousness, which I or anyone else has not been able to prove, and it's true that we can't even prove that other humans have consciousness.
But in this case, at least, we can hope that all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But as we study other species and we examine questions of perception or consciousness in general, we get into difficult terrain because the hardware doesn't match.
When a rat is in danger, it does what many other animals do: It pretends to be dead, flies or attacks.
Humans behave in a similar way, which some researchers have concluded is a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our own subjective experiences to animals.
Circuits related to human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and executive/management functions).
This vast area is more highly developed in humans than in other primates, and it seems to be completely absent in other living things.
At least in the aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, such as our sense of who we are or our ability to plan and make decisions, it is reasonable to assume that we are different from even other primates.
Another dramatic feature of man's linguistic nature is that since much of human experience is related to language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals may be excluded.
But even if language were not a determining factor in consciousness, language would certainly be a determining factor, so animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
So it's difficult to say what the other animals are conscious of.
If consciousness is not something that can be measured internally and subjectively, and if it is not something that can be analyzed based on our own experience because of the special hardware, then its research presents us with serious problems.
Most of my talk is about the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that is probably more accessible to science.
The conscious processes of animals could be studied independently of their content, and this is exactly what happens in experiments on short-term memory in primates, especially in the example of visualization.
However, in this hypothesis, also studied by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, they rely more on neural connections of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: They may be the same or not.
Interestingly, this hypothesis also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the development of visualization.
What does this mean for emotions?
I'm going to trace this back to the fact that an emotional system, like fear, is activated in the brain, which is aware of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is the mental state we are in when the activity of the defense system in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) takes over the working memory.
So, when we look at it, emotions are closely linked to areas of the cortex that are characteristic of primates and especially humans.
And with language, we have subtle degrees of perception, because with words and with language, we can distinguish and categorize states, and describe them to others besides ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, argues that emotions come from the simpler activities of the cortex and the body sensory areas of the brainstem, as does Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it can easily play a role in the emotions of species.
I can't dispute that in theory, but I think it's unprovable.
Pankseep believes that what appears to be fear in rats and humans is likely to be felt in both cases: How can we check that rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach fleeing danger, does it feel fear?
I think that just because you have similar behavior doesn't mean you have the same experience.
Although neural comparisons are helpful, rats and humans have similar brainstems, whereas cockroaches don't.
But is the brainstem responsible for emotions?
And even if we could prove it in humans, how would we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches, who knows, have feelings.
However, I don't know how to prove it.
And since their emotions are suspected to be fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I'm more interested in the emotional behavior of rats than their emotional emotions.
However, there's a lot of progress in this area at the neural level, if we measure the same in rats and humans.
Just as I don't study language and consciousness in rats, I don't study emotions because I don't know if they exist.
To others, this may seem shortsighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly running into a wall.
I'm a practical emotional guy, you know.
