Gebrselassie, who is rested, breaks his own world record
Ethiopian Haile Gebrselassie once again showed why he is considered by many to be the greatest middle- and long-distance runner of all time when he broke his own world record in Berlin on Sunday, becoming the first person to run the 42.2 kilometers in 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With his victory in a comfortable 2:03:59 on the flat track, Gebrselassie improved his previous record of 2:04:26 set in Berlin last year by 27 seconds.
By the age of 35, Gebrselassie had set the 26th world record of his career in so many different distances that he had won or set world records in almost every event from the 1500 meters to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic marathon, fearing - perhaps an over-cautiousness in retrospect - that air pollution would exacerbate his asthma problems.
Instead, he signed me up for the Berlin Marathon.
In almost perfect conditions - in sunny weather, first at 9 °C and then at 13 °C - Gebrselassie won on Sunday, at an incredible speed of 2 minutes 56 seconds per kilometre.
Since previously untrained runners like Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya have turned to longer distances, the marathon record has dropped by more than two minutes in the past decade since Brazil's Ronaldo da Costa won in Berlin in 1998 with a time of 2:06:05.
After Sunday's victory, Gebrselassie told reporters that two weeks ago he had a sprained ankle and was unable to train for two weeks.
Obviously, during the forced rest, he refreshed himself and didn't get rusty.
"I'm so happy", Gebrselassie told reporters, "I'm so happy to be here today".
"Everything was going perfectly.
I started training again a week ago, and today I had my doubts, but everything was fine".
He has received some criticism - particularly from Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival - that he uses too many auxiliary equipment in his competitions, usually avoids many world-famous marathoners, relies on pace runners as if he were running on a track, and puts world records ahead of the competition.
However, this criticism hardly diminishes Gebrselassie's greatness in the long distance.
Gebrselassie crossed the finish line in 1:02:04 with four Kenyan sprinters on Sunday.
Two leading Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, gave the rhythm to Gebrselassie after the pace runners were exhausted.
Just over 3 miles (4.8 km) from the finish, Gebrselassie sprinted one last time to knock out Kwambai, who finished second in 2:05:36, 5 minutes better than his personal best.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Kazakhstan-born Irina Mikitenko, now a German citizen, closed a remarkable year with her seventh-fastest win of 2:19:19.
The world record is held by British Paula Radcliffe with a time of 2:15:25.
Last spring, 36-year-old Mikitenko won the London Marathon by a surprise with a time of 2:24:14.
He was unable to compete in the Beijing Olympics due to a supposed back injury, but recovered quickly and won the Berlin Marathon, where he improved his individual best by five minutes, the third marathon distance he had run.
He calculated wisely and won the race, first allowing a group of four Ethiopians and Kenyans to advance and gain a considerable lead, then following them after running about 20 miles [30 km].
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second with a time of 2:21.31, while Helena Kiprop of Kenya finished third with a time of 2:25:01.
A city isolated, black pride and trials
In the Greater Orlando theme park, just a few miles from everything glittering, loud and mighty, lies a quiet little town where the pride and complexity of the African-American experience was born.
Eatonville, the first black city to integrate into the country, and the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as it was in 1935 when she described it as "a town of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guavas, and two schools, no jail".
It's a pilgrimage now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have been to the annual Zora Festival, the Eatonville celebration series honoring the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance, Hurston.
Yet in many ways, the city he described as a tourist attraction - which is also featured in the Florida Travel Guide published by the Crisis Writers' Federation Project - is separate from its surroundings.
As independent, dignified, and self-absorbed as it was in the 1930s, when, Hurston writes, urban blacks in Florida were often reluctant to share their true thoughts with white people who "know so little about us that they don't know what they're missing".
Even in the year that black presidential candidate Barack Obama encourages open discussion on the issue of race, many here are suspicious of the outsiders' gaze.
"We are very careful about how we tell our story", said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city's oldest church.
"You have to tell it right".
Eatonville has long been characterized by the paradox of victory and struggle.
It's both a historic model of black representation and a community of almost 2,400 people with poverty rates that are twice the national average.
Partly a literary hub, partly an example of the American slavery, sometimes disdained, sometimes glorified, of the Southern, urban, black culture that thrives in the shade of oak trees.
Not surprisingly, the people here are both proud and defensive.
And the image of Eatonville has been important since Zora, (that's what everyone here calls Hurston).
In books written in a frank, strong dialect - such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937) - he introduced his hometown to the world.
Five paragraphs of the Florida Guidebook have transformed the city, which sits along Route 17, from the long-forgotten center of Florida to one of the most historic sites in black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was as brave in life and literature as a drummer, introduced his readers to the business of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then to the more intimate realms.
He wrote: "To the right of the road we find the modern public school, on a brown ground with white borders, with carefully kept yards and playgrounds, maintained by Howard Miller, though he can hardly read or write".
He mentioned the widow Dash's new husband, and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and anything you might need for temporary accommodations".
So in a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with autonomy, but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
It's clear Fodor's travel guide has a different description.
That description really didn't sit well with everyone.
"Zora told things as they were", recalled Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's daughters, whom Hurston immortalized by quoting the silly songs men sang about their beauty.
He added: "Some people didn't like that".
Hurston is still remembered here as the living freak who often visited home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston stormed into the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a rumble Chevrolet, smoking cigarettes, and in long pants in a city where people still pride themselves on their dignified dress.
Most people were fascinated, Franklin said, but many were flattered.
"People were always happy to see Zora", Franklin said.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added, swinging in his chair: "I never stayed too long".
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books were no longer being reprinted.
It seemed that Eatonville, along with most of the world, had forgotten about it.
Although she was once a popular writer, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had lived before.
There were no major memorials or major public readings at Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood how much he enriched the world or what he left us", said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's 2003 biography, "In the Rainbow".
The turning point came in 1980.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-lane road through the city instead of the two-lane highway, Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in community life.
The expanding Orlando has already penetrated the interstate highway 4 on the city's western border.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, among other things, ended the community's relatively idyllic isolation.
In the 1950's, racial strife filled the community with hatred.
"A group of white boys came by and threw oranges and other things at people sitting on the side of the road", Franklin said.
"There was a lady who died in this.
They threw a melon out of a car".
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court's decision to forcibly integrate, stating that Brown v. Board of Education "offends my race more than it respects it".
Today, residents say that while the school desegregation was positive in some ways, it weakened the cohesion of Eatonville and undermined the self-confidence of young people.
"Black children are used to being killed - I remember that - by hugging their teachers in the morning and in the evening", reported N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins, executive director of the nonprofit organization Protect the Eatonville Community.
"This continued until the students and teachers came from the same place", he added.
"We didn't hug our white teacher because she was a white teacher - I mean, we had cultural differences", Nathiri said.
But human rights helped to lift up many other Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who stood up to prejudice as he did, with such exhilarating self-confidence and lines as, "How can anyone deprive himself of the pleasure of my company?
It's incomprehensible to me".
In 1975, Alice Walker wandered to Hurston's unmarked grave and began a struggle to restore her reputation.
Five years later, a well-regarded biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway appeared on the bookstore shelves, re-establishing him as one of America's leading figures.
The road project would have started just as Eatonville's most famous daughter was back in the spotlight.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw him as the savior.
In 1988, the community began organizing a Hurston Festival to show what the county was about to ruin with its mainline.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and many have returned to the celebration every January since.
A few years later, the county dropped the road project.
"The five-lane highway has given the community a new lease of life, a full speed, which is a real civic pride", said Nathiri.
Boyd put it more simply, "Zora saved Eatonville".
The victory over the road project helped to change the image the city had of itself.
And more and more people from outside the city, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer, who started going to church here in 1993, and the locals started to reassess the past.
Eatonville was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
In 2006, the new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened on the re-paved and redecorated Kennedy Avenue.
Eatonville remains Florida's quintessential city: less than 10 miles from downtown Orlando, but it sometimes feels like a suburban back street in the summer rains; it's as small as it was when 27 black families founded it in the 1880s.
(Today, 90% of the population is black.)
They're still wary of outsiders coming here looking for something to say about Eatonville's story.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things - such as Eatonville's oldest mural, painted by a white man and depicting black people working the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
In Eatonville, many - including the confident teacher Jones, who is particularly attracted to bright red - fear that their isolated community will be misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival grew in scope, so did the pride of the hometown.
Young people in particular are increasingly seeing Eatonville as Hurston saw his own race: wonderful, with problems and all, no better or worse, just as proud, creative, hardworking, crazy and confused as other racial and ethnic groups in America.
Sincere civic attachment is silenced by the words of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return after college to take a job with the local government or the police, which he feels need help.
And it seems that even younger people have learned to properly describe Eatonville, like the 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, Alondra and Alexia Kenon.
"Most people who just pass by think that this city is nothing compared to the rest", said Alondra Kenon recently after a Sunday service.
"But if you stop and take a little time to learn about its history, it's a very beautiful city".
We all speak the language of finance here in New York.
On the surface, nothing has changed.
If tourists were not concerned about the newsstands and the giant television sets in Times Square, they would not realize that they are in the midst of a storm.
They'd never realize that with their glass-walled, bee-shaped offices overhead, the bankers and hedge fund managers who hold New York City in their power are having their worst days since 1929.
Couriers still roll their metal tea carts along the sidewalks, carrying trays loaded with muffins to morning meetings.
Spanish-speaking men still roam the brick houses, carrying as human mules some 50 or so embroidered shirts hanging on a yoke-like loop across the shoulders.
Office workers are still queuing for their morning sweet pastries at the sidewalk food trucks, and it is still impossible to catch a taxi between 4 and 7 p.m. on a weekday.
I didn't feel like there was any crisis until Thursday afternoon, despite all the ominous news, I decided to open a new bank account.
I had deliberately planned to do it during the afternoon rush at my local branch of J.P. Morgan Chase, but there were already about 20 people in line.
Not at the cashier's window, where you can withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service counter, where old customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to Macy's, and new customers open bank accounts.
Many before me - I learned later from Starr, the banker I was "assigned" - lined up with the same intent as I did.
But unlike me, they've already taken their money out of smaller banks in their home state, like New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
Money was taken from so-called savings banks (such as housing cooperatives), credit unions, and small-town savings banks that operate in only one state and supposedly treat their customers like family members.
In the last year, 15 of these banks went silently bankrupt.
In recent days, Washington Mutual, a $327 billion bank, has been on the brink of bankruptcy, and as New Yorkers headed home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, was looking for a $440 billion savings-saving buyer.
The office and store workers in front of me, afraid of another collapse, transferred their money to what seemed to be a safe haven, the bank that makes the most capital injection purchases on Wall Street.
The average New Yorker has become an expert in finance over the last few weeks.
A woman at the local Chinese department store on the phone talked about the bankrupt Lehman Brothers and its big-looking CEO, Dick Fuld, as if she were complaining about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed, 50-year-old janitor of my block, switched the subject, not talking about Brad and Angelina or my food delivery, as we usually do.
After I went to the bank, he said to me: "I have invested all my savings in financial market instruments.
I'm not taking any chances".
Muslim graves desecrated as Austria tilted to the right
Heinz-Christian Strache of the right-wing Austrian Freedom Party and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang party attended a demonstration in Antwerp on Thursday 17 January 2008 in which the organization "Variants Against the Islamic Conquest" was introduced.
They marched with signs that mimicked traffic signs, depicting mosques crossed by red lines.
Police believe far-right extremists are responsible for the desecration of Austrian Muslim cemeteries, which occurred on the same weekend that far-right parties made significant gains in the country's parliamentary elections.
More than 90 graves were severely damaged at Trauni Cemetery outside Linz sometime between Friday night and this morning, police said.
The perpetrators painted Jewish symbols such as the Star of David on some graves, but investigators say they were merely trying to hide their extremist motives, which stem from hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It's not clear if the incident could be connected in any way to the election.
