Meanwhile, Austria is holding a conscience test following yesterday's parliamentary elections, in which the language of the political balance has shifted to the right.
The two far-right parties, which won almost 30 percent of the vote, the Freedom Party and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, campaigned for a strong anti-immigration law, and some of their slogans were labeled xenophobic by their critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the leader of the Freedom Party, which won more than 18 percent of the vote, has expressed displeasure with the campaign against headscarves and burqas, as well as the food allegedly associated with Islam.
