"I'm not taking pictures on stage because I want to introduce the artist from a personal point of view"
No makeup, no hair or dance shoes.
The great masters of flamenco, close to the body, without the excitement of the performance: to get to know the ordinary faces of the dancers.
On the one hand, the artist.
Ordinary people, on the other hand.
And these two sides are not separated, except in those intimate moments, away from the audience, when we can experience a personal movement, capture the depth of a caught gaze, or marvel at the beauty of the still but expressive hands of an artist who is preparing to perform on stage.
In his photography series Flamenco-people, German Günther Bauer combines the theatricality of singers, dancers and guitarists with this less-known, mundane side of the masters.
Through the photographs, he shows the unique iconography of flamenco from different angles.
The exhibition, which is part of the month of Flamenco Photography, "reflects the growing international significance of flamenco", says the creator, adding that the Flamenco-people "can be played by anyone, because when the viewer sees the images, he is surprised that these images do not represent the artists in a typical way.
These people on the street are artists who can bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and captivate the audience.
But stage photography is not the way to capture their personalities.
Their personality and character are deep within them.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personalities of the great flamenco artists through the camera".
The Cante de las Minas festival gave Bauer a boost to his long journey in 1997, during which he took portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers with a disc camera.
This portrait is a classic example of photography, thanks to its camera and choice of subject.
However, the use of various stylistic means breaks with traditional pictorial representation and suggests modernity. The following thought faithfully reflects Bauer's view of flamenco: "It is a music with traditional roots, but it changes day by day and is always fascinating".
It's not the dance, it's not the singing or the music itself, it's the personality of the artist, the character that fascinates the audience.
The main theme of the works that can be seen at El Fotomatá Gallery these days is the search for an encounter with the essence, the artistic magic, which becomes visible through the way of perception, existence and representation.
The names of famous flamenco figures, including Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, are the hallmarks of this photography collection, which features almost sixty artists.
The project has also become a flamenco anthology, which will soon be published in an album of portraits presented at the exhibition.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the series "Portraits of Veteran Athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concept of Flamenco-people is somewhat different, the photographer adds: "I really like to photograph people, get to know them and enter their lives for a longer or shorter moment.
I think the hardest part of photography is portraiture.
You meet people, personalities, who sometimes you don't even know, or who only have a few minutes to take pictures.
But despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my vision come true.
The exhibition, entitled Flamenco-people, selected from contemporary flamenco portraits, will be on view until 16 October at the El Fotomatata Gallery, located at 20 calle de la Mata, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules.
