Recurring drunk drivers will be required to install "Alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior would require a car to be fitted with a device that would prevent the vehicle from starting if the driver was drunk or not blowing into the device after three drunk driving violations.
The proposal was submitted in June and is currently being examined by the Public Prosecutor's Office, which has said that the pilot project will last for one year.
As the project aims to restore traffic, the driver will also have to take a repeat course on traffic education.
In addition to the DG for Transport Safety, the DG for Transport and the Foundation for the Automotive Safety Institute of Technology (FITSA) are also involved in the experiment.
Statistics show that 30 to 75 percent of repeat drunk drivers get back in their cars.
This would be prevented by Alcolock, because the system linked to the vehicle determines the alcohol level of the air inhaled.
The cost of the equipment, which is more than 1000 euros, would be borne by the offender.
A 2007 study in the USA showed that vehicles equipped with such devices can reduce the number of infractions by up to 65% in the first year after they are fitted.
In Spain, it is estimated that this rule could save 115 lives a year.
The measure focuses on infringements for two reasons: first, it makes it easier to prevent them from becoming criminal offences;
On the other hand, it is easier to introduce because the legal reform is implemented at the usual pace, while the necessary criminal reform would require an amendment to the Basic Law.
The instrument is not yet commercially available on the Spanish market, although it has been installed in some industrial and public vehicles in a pilot mode.
