Blood is safe again
Yesterday, Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary, and President Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate, as Héma-Québec has now become one of the safest and most efficient blood donation societies in the world.
Most important, he regained the trust of the people, which had been shaken by the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980's and 1990's.
As is well known, the national blood supply treated by the Canadian Red Cross was infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980's.
After the tragedy and the general uproar, the Government of Canada, led by Justice Horace Krever, launched a formal investigation in February 1994 to shed light on the circumstances leading up to the tragedy and to formulate recommendations for avoiding future similar cases.
While Justice Krever was late in submitting his report, some provinces set up their own committees to design a new blood system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Commission has fulfilled this task.
The Gélineau and Krever reports have led to the creation of two blood supply services in Canada: one, Héma-Québec, which serves Quebec, and the other, the Canadian Blood Supply Company, which serves all the other provinces and two territories.
"When Héma-Québec began operations in 1998, only 38 percent of the people had confidence in Quebec's blood supply system", recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
"In the years that followed, however, improvements in the safety of blood products and our work in the field helped us to regain people's trust". Décary is proud to report that by early 2008, nearly 94% of the Québec population had trusted Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary does not forget that "trust is an extremely fragile thing".
Héma-Québec has been operating on a precautionary basis since its creation on 28 September 1998.
During this period, several cases of human infection with the new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, known as rubella, were discovered in Europe, says the doctor who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
"We had no idea if this disease was transmitted through blood.
So we relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which is that if we're unsure, and there's a risk of serious disease, we should use exclusionary measures, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which causes brain damage and inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, we did not accept blood from persons who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
And a few years ago, it was determined beyond a doubt that the disease is also transmitted through the blood.
This case convinced us that the precautionary principle made sense".
In 1999, a technique that allows for a much more sensitive diagnosis of the HIV virus came onto the market, the nucleic acid assay (NAT), which can detect the virus directly in the blood of donors, rather than the antibodies to the virus that previously used assays were based on.
"The NAT test has shortened the window period from infection to detection in the blood using our technical tools", explains the expert.
This period was reduced to less than a week.
This significantly reduced the risk of blood donors unknowingly contaminating the blood supply and making it undetectable.
These developments have greatly reduced the risk of spreading AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of someone getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
"In other words, we would have to distribute 12 million blood products to someone who is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products each year, it would take more than 24 years for one such case to occur and for someone to become infected with the HIV virus through a blood product.
I think that today anyone can accept or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore health, says Héma-Québec's number one executive.
"The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
You never know what new pathogens are going to enter your system.
It was only last year that the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the bloodstream through insect bites.
Therefore, we must be on alert at all times", continued Dr Décary, stressing that in addition to the slaughter reserves, Héma-Québec must ensure that there is a sufficient permanent reserve.
"As the population ages, so do the needs.
As cancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also affects the blood donor population, with only 3% of the population of Quebec eligible to donate blood.
However, any healthy person at least 18 years of age who is eligible may donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On the average, 14 percent of applicants will not accept blood because they have AIDS or malaria, and those who have been to a country where malaria is rampant are not eligible to donate for a year.
"This 3 percent is enough to meet the needs of hospitals.
It's very rare that we run out of supplies.
But we need to increase the number of blood donors as the existing ones get older, because they can't give blood after a while.
But it is very difficult to convince people to donate blood, and even more difficult to keep them and get them to become regular blood donors.
In today's fast-paced world, one hardly has a single hour to go and donate blood".
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec not only supplies blood products but also human tissues, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin tissue, which are used almost exclusively in the treatment of severe burns.
These tissues are analysed, transformed and frozen and then deposited at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public stem cell bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which was previously treated as medical waste, can be used to produce blood rich in stem cells, which can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated the arrival of our 1,000th umbilical cord blood sample a few weeks ago, and we plan to collect over 1,000 new samples each year.
We will probably start offering these for transplantation early next year", explains Dr. Décary, who says that the umbilical cord blood collection program is very popular today.
"Many mothers are sad that they cannot afford to do this" - indeed, Héma-Québec cannot afford to make this complex and costly program available in all hospitals in Quebec.
