Charest's Northern Attempts
The Prime Minister does not rule out that the election will start this year
Shortly after the Liberal Party's meeting, Jean Charest traveled yesterday to Jean-Talon, Quebec, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc (left), is poised to win the midterm elections scheduled for today.
"Strict our last great northern frontier" is the ambitious long-term goal set by Jean Charest at the Liberal Party's rally in Lévis, Quebec, yesterday.
During his lecture, behind his back, they were projecting a series of images similar to "Moulin à images".
The three giant projectors were taking one stunning shot at a time: hydroelectric dams, mining, Quebec on Google Maps, maps...
These spectacular devices are used during election season.
The Prime Minister, however, refused to guarantee that the election would not start this autumn, although he added that his schedule was very tight.
The "Northern Plan" is the fourth pillar of the Prime Minister's "vision" for the future of Québec, which is embodied in a "new economic area", including a labour agreement with France, a Canada-Europe agreement and several planned agreements with Ontario.
In recent times, the opening to the North (i.e. the northern area starting at 49° latitude) has been a frequent feature of speeches by the Prime Minister, but he has never given a lecture on the subject.
The head of state, however, confined himself to explaining why he considers the North "a treasure trove of enormous potential", but did not mention the timing, investment amounts or a specific order of priority for future projects.
It highlighted only a few development opportunities: in particular, hydropower, forestry and, in particular, mining, which is further stimulated by the growth of the countries in lockdown and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
The north is home to "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamonds", says Charest.
This territory, "twice the size of France", is our territory, Quebec.
It is not only with us, but within us", the head of state repeated, stressing that he wants to create a national founding myth.
He stressed that the development of Quebec was largely determined by the relationship with the North: the gold rush in Abitibi, the planning of Quebec, the James Bay...
"This is ours, our future!" he added, after taking a break from the stage to look at the huge map behind him.
The north, which covers 70% of Quebec's territory, includes part of Labrador, which Quebec has always claimed, the premier said at a news conference.
"This is our historic position, reaffirmed by all governments.
There is a line on which there has been no agreement for a long time and if the opportunity arises, I will reaffirm the same resolution on behalf of the Government.'
On the other hand, "in the face of climate change, we must rethink our view of the North", said the prime minister, referring to the Northwest Passage, which opens every year as a result of the melting of the Arctic ice.
In the Prime Minister's view, in this new geopolitical environment, the occupation of the territory is an important task.
What about the natives, the Indians, the Eskimos?
The Prime Minister stated that the Québec government is paying special attention to them and that the plan will bring many benefits, especially to young people.
Two ministers from different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (later a delegate from the Parti Québécois in Unguai), have already started the consultation with some 30 local communities.
An inter-ministerial committee, headed by Benoît Pelletier, also started its work, with Julie Boulet (Minister for Transport and Natural Resources) playing an important role.
The Prime Minister does not rule out a large-scale meeting, "not necessarily a summit", where "a common vision is created".
The development of the North would otherwise be carried out in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
The Northern Plan will be coordinated, systematic and environmentally friendly", the Prime Minister promised.
Jean Charest described this "vision" as being in line with the ideas of the liberal prime ministers who preceded him.
"Like the liberals of the past, we think differently: our goal is to turn challenges into new opportunities for growth and development".
This was one of the recurring themes of the weekend which began with a big cocktail party on Friday to celebrate the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage's election as party leader.
One of the resolutions adopted proposes that the Beauharnois power station be renamed the Adélard-Godbout dam.
"Politicians in our party, including Godbout, who founded Hydro-Québec, Lesage, who led the Quiet Revolution and the nationwide expansion of hydroelectric power, and Bourassa, known as the father of James Bay, all knew how to shape the future", said Jean Charest.
At the press conference, he quoted another, true, conservative work, namely John Diefenbaker's programme "Roads to the North", which was the programme of the Prime Minister from 1957 to 1963.
With regard to the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric dam project, President Charest stressed that the start-up is planned for 2012.
"Keep it between us, but I plan to be there", he told his followers, and his statement was met with a roar of applause.
The Prime Minister, who in April said that there would be no elections in 2008 and probably in 2009, did not rule out the possibility of a vote in the autumn of this year, which the law allows him to do.
He stressed, however, that his schedule was already full, having taken on duties at the Chinese meeting of the Federal Council and the Quebec-New York summit.
The weekend party convention proved to be an excellent platform for the Liberal president to discuss the nationalist resolutions, which were passed almost without thinking, especially the "constitutional aspirations" that the Liberal Party demands, in particular, recognition of "Quebec's peculiar character" in the Constitution.
I also want Quebec to appoint the members of the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission, and I want those members to have veto power over decisions made in Quebec.
The opposition, however, was skeptical of the main points of the Northern Plan.
The leader of Parti Québécois, Paulina Marois, re-launched the Northern Quebec development policy introduced by the Landry government in 2001.
According to Marois, the liberal government that came to power in 2003 refused to apply this policy.
If they had not done so, "we would have been much further ahead today", said Mrs Marois, in agreement with Françoise Mercure, who stood as a candidate in the Jean-Talon vote today.
The ADQ opposition party supports the government's adoption of the Northern Plan.
"We want this to be more than a show", said Sébastien Proulx, the party leader who replaced Mario Dumont, who is returning from his leave today.
Letters - A Disgraced Country
Vic Toews, Harper's cabinet minister (who happens to be the "Justice" minister) had the audacity last summer to call Louise Arbourt a "disgrace" to Canada.
To insult a woman who has fought tirelessly for the truth and deserves our admiration, says a lot about the people around the Prime Minister and about Stephen Harper himself.
So this is our government, which is the only Western country that has not returned its own citizens from the Guantanamo concentration camp.
This is a government that absolutely ignores the fact that Omar Khadr was a teenager at the time of the alleged crimes.
This is the only government that, despite Canada's signature of the Geneva Convention, has refused to do so and let a child soldier languish in inhumane conditions.
The only government that puppets justice while investigating the guilt of an accused.
Remember that UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Canadian Bar Association are also calling for Omar Khadr to be returned to Canada so that he can have a fair trial.
And our government is turning a blind eye to torture: it doesn't care that a young adult is already completely ruined, and that years of torture have probably sealed his fate for life.
Although we don't realize it yet, our rights, our freedom, and our democracy are being subtly destroyed. "Democracy": Harper repeats this word over and over again, which sounds like a mere empty word from her mouth.
The time has come when there is no morality: any Canadian citizen can be arbitrarily beaten, tortured and imprisoned at the discretion of a leader of a government that has been in the minority (and what will happen after October 14...?).
Many voters believe that salvation can be found in a party that glorifies virtue, law and order, but they fail to see that this government is trampling on the values that have given our country its reputation and dignity.
Dear Mr Toews, shame is this - don't look elsewhere.
Opinion - Barrick Gold's speech at the Orwell
In the September 17 issue of Le Devoir, a letter appeared from Patrick J. Garver, the vice president and CEO of Barrick Gold in Canada.
Following Orwell's analysis, Garver states that the world's largest gold mining company has filed a $6 million defamation suit against three authors and a small-time publisher to initiate what he calls a "public dispute".
Although judges are independent and impartial, their decisions - especially in defamation cases - are based, not on the truth, but on the law.
It's no surprise that Garver was silent about this fundamental difference.
Is it really the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate, to ruin anyone who disagrees with him?
Regardless of the outcome of the lawsuit, the authors and publishers of Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to defend and fight an unequal battle, with the other side having an army of lawyers backed by the almost inexhaustible resources of the mining industry.
In such an unequal fight, however, the tactic of ruining the defendant and making a friendly agreement is often employed, not only to silence the opponents but also to intimidate those who would try to reenter the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, they should have spoken out publicly.
Although in many other countries where Barrick Gold operates, this is done differently, in Canada the parties to the dispute do not usually beat each other, but rather express their thoughts.
So all the mine would have done was open up its books and files and prepare for a real debate in the press, media, publications, paying for independent research groups that could shed light on the issue.
But it seems Barrick Gold doesn't trust the public and is making a move to erase petitions and letters written to defend the writers of Noir Canada.
Mr. Garver, could you explain how you can initiate a "public" debate while ignoring the opinion of this public?
In the Vice President's mind, that word probably means just the well-paid lawyers, not the entire population of Canada, and that narrows the meaning of the word a lot.
In a democratic state, even those who insult others are entitled to freedom of speech.
Barrick Gold, however, does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public support for the authors and publishers of Noir Canada is primarily because it condemns the mining industry's harsh practices.
The public is willing to hear Barrick and pass judgment, but on the basis of civilized reasoning rather than a lawsuit that many would prefer to silence. (In relation to the term "public debate", by the way, Barrick Gold recently wrote to Noir Canada's authors to refrain from using this term.)
Beyond Garver's surrealist arguments, the Barrick Gold process is an open assault on the freedom of academic research and the pursuit of truth, which are the building blocks of any democratic society.
The procedure as a whole denies the right to cite credible sources, to debate some of the facts and their interpretations, which form the basis of intellectual activities.
If in a country like Canada, you can only study and discuss subjects that are not of interest to the rich corporations of today, with the burden of litigation, who will have the courage to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wants an open and transparent debate, it should do so according to the scientific standards that the authors of Noir Canada have adopted.
You have the right to answer.
We have long been able to deal with debate, disagreement and conflict in our academic circles.
Barrick Gold's reckless conduct shows that, contrary to what it claims, it is reluctant to engage in open debate.
This is a loss for both the academic world and the Canadian public debate establishment, and it is time for governments to finally introduce measures to limit legal proceedings for such abuse.
The Wall Street bailout, the Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, Republican and Democrat, finally reached agreement yesterday on an economic bailout, the largest such plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The $700 billion plan to stem the financial crisis that has been raging on Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
The main elements of the plan are: more effective control by the representatives of the implementation; new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the public money earmarked; new provisions to keep the number of houses seized for non-payment at a level; access to the salaries of the managers of the companies receiving aid.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the U.S. House Nancy Pelosi, and Judd Gregg, the Republican congressman who was in the hearing yesterday, announced the good news minutes before midnight after the two-day marathon trial ended.
"We've made great strides toward a solution that will work effectively in the markets", said Henry Paulson, a representative in the Bush administration.
"We did it all to save the real economy and the American people from the current crisis that is plaguing Wall Street", the Democrat explained.
"The most important consideration is that if we don't do this, there will be tremendous shock, chaos and disorder in the daily lives of Americans", said Rep. Judd Gregg, R-N.Y.
The negotiations have been accelerated in the last few hours, fearing that another failure would have a detrimental effect on investor sentiment.
They've given you a deadline for the deal until the stock market opens this morning.
Two presidential candidates who joined the negotiations late showed a willingness to agree, but expressed displeasure at the escalation to extremes.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama credited himself with expanding the agreement with elements such as provisions on homeownership preservation or paying the directors of state-aided companies.
"When we ask taxpayers to take certain extraordinary steps because of other people's irresponsibility, it's not a very pleasant thing.
But these steps are necessary", he noted on an American television program.
And when his opponent, John McCain, was asked by another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, he said, "I'd like to know the details, but I hope so".
"From what I have read in bold, it is clear that this is something we all need to digest and move on from.
The possibility of doing nothing is simply unacceptable", he said.
The $700 billion plan would use taxpayer money to buy the dubious claims of American financial institutions, somewhat risky, unsold assets.
The plan was preceded by a 14-month crisis triggered by the real estate bubble, which led first to the collapse of risky mortgages (secondary mortgages), then to other debt-bearing (commercial) securities, and finally to the freezing of liquidity and the collapse of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft agreement was defeated by a group of Republican lawmakers last week.
It seems we've managed to get out of this impasse since the Democrats agreed to let the government provide certain "toxic" assets to troubled companies rather than buy them.
To satisfy all members of Congress, the plan included a provision that if the government had to bear losses under the program for five years, it could impose new taxes to recoup its resources.
As part of the new plan, a $250 billion installment would be paid first, followed by another $100 billion if the president deems it necessary.
The remaining $350 billion would have to be approved by a second vote of Congress.
In return for the help, Washington will acquire a stake in the subsidiaries, which will give it a dividend on the profits, which it can sell after the crisis subsides.
