The psychology of over-bid: why are we giving out more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overvalue the goods.
The neuroeconomic basis for this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior has been revealed by researchers at New York University, who are neuroscientists and economists.
Their study, published in the journal Science, found that people who don't want to fall behind in a type of competition, such as an eBay auction, are more likely to pay too high a price.
The research was trying to map out the neural patterns of this "play" by experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers participated in a lottery, the other in a playful auction, while the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, the participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the other party is the main player, the striatum, a complex of the subclavian artery, is activated when the game is lost.
This brain region, among other functions, is involved in the "self-reward" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, the researchers believe that the price increase can be explained by avoiding the intense reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists in the research team also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this case, three groups bid against one partner in different circumstances.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made their bets.
Another group was promised that if they won the game and left, they would receive an additional $15 in prize money.
The third group, on the other hand, had just received $15 before the auction, but the members of the group lost that money in a losing auction.
The difference between the two groups was therefore only that one group was emphasized on winning and the other on losing.
But proving the neuroscientists' hypothesis, the members of the "against-loss" team were willing to bet higher than the control and the "win" groups.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
They have hitherto only explained the phenomena of auctions with the joy of winning and the avoidance of risk.
Only neurological imaging has helped to resolve the contradiction between these two theories, so that we have now come to a third explanation", states Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When Should You See a Doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people are chronically infected with hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease is listed as one of the leading causes of death in Hungary.
You can count on hundreds of thousands of hepatitis cases here, but you only treat seven thousand, because patients often don't know they're infected.
Hepatitis is a collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
They have many similarities in their symptoms, including hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases are different.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e. g. contaminated food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (sputum, vaginal secretions, saliva).
Travellers should be vaccinated against A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated food, usually accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal complaints, nausea.
After this, yellowing of the skin and the white of the eye, light faeces, and dark urine may occur, and healing may take two to three weeks.
Worldwide, one million people die each year from the more serious form of the disease, hepatitis B, which causes liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected persons receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences, leading to liver failure and liver cancer if left untreated.
Most infected people do not know they have the disease because the virus subtly destroys liver cells, and in many cases the first symptoms do not appear until 20 or 30 years later.
So then it's very important to have early prevention, to have regular screening.
Three groups have much higher rates than the average: people who received blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and tattooers.
The number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus worldwide is now estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory test, it is advisable to consult your GP if you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
If the disease is detected early, it can be cured, the virus can be eliminated from the body, and the infectious process can be stopped and cancer can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first celebrated in 2004 by patient organizations around the world.
It aims to raise awareness of chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection.
Does believing in God hurt less?
A recent study suggests that religious faith acts as a kind of pain reliever, which may have eased the deaths of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment to study how belief in God affects people's perception of pain, reports Britain's Telegraph.
In a rather bizarre study, 12 Catholics and as many atheists were given electric shocks while they were all studying a painting of the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholics were able to rule out most of the pain.
Thanks to the technology of scanning the human brain, it was also found that the Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The study is the first in a series of studies involving academics as well as scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
The test was carried out precisely by attaching a spark device to the left hand of the subject, which provided the electric shock.
The researchers asked participants to look intently at two paintings, the 17th-century Virgin Mary by Sassoferrato and Leonardo da Vinci's 15th-century painting Lady with Hermeline.
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a religious mood among the faithful, while the da Vinci image was chosen because it was not too different from the others and was thought to have a calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 electric shocks in four consecutive sessions, while either viewing the religious-themed or the general image.
Catholics reported that during the vision of the Virgin Mary they felt "safe", "cared for", and "rested, filled with peace".
When viewing a religious image, they reported 12 percent less pain than when viewing Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who participated in the study, believes that you can achieve a similar effect with any powerful image, even with atheists, just by finding the right photo.
"We should find an image that they feel very positive about, like a mother or a father", the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should, and in many cases does, change our personality", Wright added.
After all the great results, the question is, if you show people a picture of the Madonna by Leonardo, or by a similar painter, how would that affect their pain management?
Would a quality Virgin Mary view mean even better results?
You are what you share
On your 10th birthday, Google can tell you that you have as much in your pocket as the sky above your head, where you've been on vacation, what you've done, what you're interested in.
And that's still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's top people.
But for those skeptics who see parallels to the Orwellian nightmare, they don't see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's ultimate goal is to collect even more personal data about its users, which is necessary to keep up with the original goal of the founders of Google, which was to "get all the information in the world into a system".
The spokesman for Google said that after 10 years of world-shaking work, the company is still in the early stages of managing all the information.
When asked what happens in five years, Schmidt said he would like Google to be able to answer questions like, "What am I going to do tomorrow?" or "What kind of job would I really be?" But until then, software can't answer these seemingly simple questions because it doesn't know enough about the user.
Not all internet users are aware that search terms are recorded precisely when searching the internet, the IP address from which they were searched and the page from which they left after searching.
For example, Personalized Search, launched two years ago, allows users to store their own browsing history, look back at what they searched for, what they clicked on, and in the long run, generate much more personalized results for them - the same logic that will be used in Recommendations, where the system recommends products and services to us based on our previously stated and recorded preferences.
What if my data is used against me, if they see what I do? ask users who are worried about Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, it's the potential power of the company that's the scarecrow, not the guilt, the fear of punishment, the desire for freedom, even the rebellion against power that triggers the backlash from the netizens.
However, it is a confirmed fact that all search terms are not only recorded but can be transferred to third parties where justified, and that in such legal cases there is no protection of the personal rights of Internet users.
Perhaps the most notorious example of this in recent times was the coordinated crackdown on Brazilian pedophiles, in which Google provided the Brazilian government with identifying information about pedophiles from its social networking site, Orkut.
Privacy-conscious netizens, however, were able to raise their voices in May when the company, in partnership with the electronic rights group EFF, successfully argued in court against the FBI that Google could no longer be compelled by any provision of the Constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully fought off some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms, which it had won by citing the reauthorization of the Child Protection Act passed years earlier, but failed to obtain individual user search lists or a complete two-month list of websites and keywords.)
So Google's judgment is quite controversial: it's being lashed out at by those who are afraid to give their personal data because they feel their privacy and privacy is being compromised by starting to use Google services and by rebelling against the multicultural companies that glow in the conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its drive to bring together enthusiastic computer fans, activists, users in many countries sees the next generation of big companies as a "growing corporation" as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, which is set to take over the world with Windows, no matter how hard it is to fight for the same goal.
This may be because, unlike Microsoft, Google doesn't ask users for an ID, doesn't charge for their applications, and the open, free, constantly updated source code and software package makes it look much more accessible, younger, cooler than the official software giant's practice.
But it could also be that geeks are clearly seeing the very problematic relationship between privacy and the Internet, which is exactly what one of the most talked about keywords of the last few years, Web 2.0, has brought about.
Because Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, about intentionally leaving a trail behind and using the channels of communication we have, and while the scale of those channels varies from individual to individual, the point is the same: we show ourselves.
The average teenager can have a profile on multiple social media sites, from Facebook to Xangá, linking them to other services like Twitter, or to last.fm, which lists their music habits, and then linking them to tracking systems like FriendFeed or Blip.fm, or running a blog that automatically shows up their latest photo galleries, which they store on Flickr or Picasa.
While there are many examples of how a girlfriend can easily tell from the morning photo stream of their mutual circle of friends who her cheating boyfriend spent the evening with, or how she can fire an employee just because he writes his honest opinion on top management on her blog, I'm sure the concept of privacy has been completely reevaluated by now.
Living online is about what you show yourself, and that's the basic premise behind the behavior of today's young people.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least avoid the Google monopoly, can do it (starting with, for example, Scroogle, which uses Google's search engine but also intentionally leaves no trace).
For example, there are a lot of people who deliberately don't sign up for social networks so that they can't be found, and Google's online apps, from word processors to image managers to newsreaders, can be replaced by alternative versions that don't connect to huge server parks and don't make us the best profile ever.
The public isn't exactly waiting in the wings for Google to show you the protein in your teeth.
At $156 billion today, the company is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense ad interfaces threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, and the accelerating pace of services introduced is causing severe headaches not only for Microsoft but also for many other software developers.
Critics, however, find that these have some disturbing counterparts: for example, the top management has flatly rejected the employees' protest after doubling the company's childcare fee, the management has found it too expensive to feed the employees as many times as they like per day, but all this is overshadowed by the fact that Google back in 2006 stood up to the Chinese government and, according to their agreement, the company filters any findings that offend good taste or the interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company's internal rules is that they don't announce a new service in advance until it's ready to go, but it's certain that the problems that are likely to arise in the coming months and years will move the world to a new level: while some believe that Google's book and magazine scanning and archiving project has reached the point where the company will soon face the U.S. Supreme Court, others fear the health system, where we can build a complete health profile based on our previous findings, our doctors and our problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database could provide a good foundation for the next generation of science fiction writers, as the popular novel by Cory Doctorow, Scroogled, describes in a point-and-click Orwellian manner a future in which a human can only be approached with alarming accuracy from Google's data.
