The intelligent car mimics the flight of a dune
What better way to develop collision avoidance technology than by mimicking the obstacle sensors found in the natural world?
Like the bees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, bumblebees gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea of how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C bio-replicated car robot control system, a robotic mini car that has been endowed with bee-like properties, with the ultimate goal of helping to develop a system that eliminates all collisions.
Each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space while flying, which is actually very similar to our safety casing", explained Kazuhhiro Doi, brand director of technology PR and research development at the exhibition.
It is important for the complex eye of the bee, which can see in all directions at angles of more than 300 degrees.
To replicate the complex function of the eye, engineers came up with the idea of a laser rangefinder.
This detects obstacles within 2 metres of the 180-degree field of view in front of the BR23C, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into a collision avoidance operation.
In a split second, the robot detects the obstacle and, by mimicking the bee's movements, immediately changes direction by turning its wheels as far as necessary to avoid a collision.
Unlike any current system, this evasive maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"Without this, the car-robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car-robot project.
It should react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety shields, a layer within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process has to reflect what a bee does in order to avoid other bees.
This process should take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot be upward, downward or transverse, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the invertibility of the wheels.
Instead of the infinite opportunity for bees to avoid other bees, the robot was used to rotate and accelerate and slow down.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries which are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer life than the lithium-ion version.
Andoh says that what's important is the instinctive intelligent response, not the ability to process data, much less to store it.
This device only needs to process and respond to a few incoming signals per second.
You don't need to store them, and you react with intuitive logic based on the data from previous maneuvers, so you're only using a few dozen kilobytes of memory all the time.
You don't need gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be available in series production cars within 10 years.
Further applications may include the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to guide the car to its intended destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
