'It is a completely independent committee, with representation from all political, social and cultural perspectives,' emphasises Alemanno, 'and it is its task to develop proposals for the development of Rome, which can be relied upon by the political decision-makers, i.e. the Assembly and the Municipal Commission.
There is no conflict of jurisdiction, we just wanted a platform where big plans for the benefit of Rome could be born.
In March, after completing its work, the committee will be dissolved, as it has a mandate for a limited period.
In June, we will present a strategic plan based on the work of the Commission "The Future of the Capital of Rome", the Mayor-General stated.
To those who dismiss the Commission's work as unnecessary, referring to the fact that the expert opinion it has drawn up is not binding, Alemanno replies: 'It all depends on the work the Commission will do and the quality of the proposals it puts on the table.
If the standard is right, as in France with the Attali Commission, which I am sure is true in Rome, the contribution it makes will play an important role.
The power of politics is often dispersed in the handling of daily affairs and in dealing with the emergencies that arise from time to time.
We, on the other hand, look further, taking into account the long-term perspective, and we plan for the longer term, and we are committed to the development and future of Rome".
The mayor of Rome wishes to emphasise that 'this Commission cannot be considered a useless 'water-man', since it is completely free of charge, and will not cost the citizens of Rome a single euro, but rather serves as a stimulus and aims to attract the best minds of the capital'.
According to Alemanno, "there is a need for an open and flexible strategic framework that allows our city to make the leap of quality it so badly needs, with a unified mindset about its future".
The future, which the mayor of Rome emphasizes "will be not limited to the current municipal framework but will look much further ahead", is not only the future metropolis and capital status, but also "the role that Rome can and must play as the capital of Europe and the Mediterranean".
