USA: The economic collapse is already felt by journalists, it's time for restrictions in the publishing industry, and many people blame the Internet for the "death" of print.
The Pew Research Center asked 500 American journalists what they thought about the future status and intellectual power of their profession.
Well, right now, almost every journalist is pessimistic about their own future.
However, they did not explicitly state that their concerns with regard to authenticity would have been reduced.
They don't feel as isolated as they used to.
The problem for American journalists is money.
They say the 2008 crisis is the failure of a weak economic model.
The other serious problem is the newsroom, which is restricted to newspaper publishing houses.
