The elite are in danger
The phenomenon was already felt a few days ago when the House of Representatives did not vote on the $700 billion bailout package put forward by the White House: a significant number of Americans were more interested, and still are, in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is corroborated by yesterday's New York Times reporting that the current crisis has led to a split within the Republican Party, which is showing a growing divide between the traditional, restrained East Coast stance in favor of federal institutions and business circles and the new, increasingly anti-Washington and anti-global financial stance in the central and southern states.
This line of thinking was critically expressed in the House vote mentioned in the introduction.
But this is only one of many significant changes that the economic reorganization that is still taking place is anticipating or allowing to be foreseen, not only in the United States but throughout the Western world and perhaps beyond.
It seems that the crisis, in the United States and in Europe, is only accelerating the phenomena that have been lurking for some time, that are consolidating in this new atmosphere and finally coming to light.
The first of these is the re-actualization, the reintroduction of the dual category of state sovereignty in the public consciousness, in a sort of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis affects banking and financial institutions which, while maintaining close links with foreign countries, are primarily, and quite broadly, dragging people and families who live in one country, one state.
This, however, presents a direct political challenge for those in power: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people who are also voters.
So while the crisis may seem global in an economic sense, it is almost exclusively national in a political sense.
Political internationalism seems to have essentially been stranded: the European Union, which is lagging behind in its inability to define a single political direction, is a striking example of this.
So everyone is waiting for the national governments to intervene, the bailout, the recovery and the new rules, but most of all the opening up of the monetary funds: because in a crisis, only individual states have the economic resources, the financial stockpile that can make things right.
They have the means and the authority to use them: in the given circumstances, they have two resources of inestimable value, which probably no other market and no international organisation will ever have to such an extent.
The new emphasis on nation-states, which has been created by the crisis, is also in full accord with the fact that recent economic growth has given increasing importance to a factor closely linked to this element: territorial character.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had entered the abstract world of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, and we were convinced that the global financial world was destined to dominate the world, we suddenly had to realize that our future was increasingly dependent on things that are not the least abstract, like water, crops and oil.
Things that can be transported from one side of the planet to the other, but they can be completely confined to a confined place, a confined area.
So whoever dominates the field has a lot more cards than whoever was unfortunately born in a place where there is no crops, no oil, no water.
And so I'm going to move on to the second innovation, which is a kind of fault line.
When you say territory, state, government, you're necessarily saying politics, in other words, leadership.
From this point of view, the economic crisis seems to produce two overlapping phenomena:
On the one hand, the objective recognition that we need authentic leadership, people who can take control of events.
On the other hand, the current leadership, especially the economic leaders, have been completely unfit and have shown that there is still much to be done.
The two together have even deeper implications and are in some ways more disturbing: the feelings of indebtedness, impatience, incompetence and isolation that are affecting the entire leadership elite in more and more Western countries.
So it seems that there is a growing belief among the population that the time of the social elite that has been at the top is over, before they have taken their actions, their experiences, their way of life, their culture, in the complex sense of the word, and they are becoming more and more alienated from the opinion of the majority.
In short, the demand for leadership, in its enveloped form, is fuelling a wide-ranging but powerful delegitimization movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system, manifested in unexpected "riots" by voters or in recent sudden changes in public sentiment, such as the rise of the Conservatives to power in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, or the Bush rebellion against US congressmen (and perhaps the victory of the Italian right).
It seems that the traditional elite, with their parties and programs, and even if you could say their habits and their media and their prestigious intellectuals, are less and less understanding and therefore less and less able to represent what has been happening in the deepest layers of Western society for some time.
Yet, to speak of "the impending revolt of the masses" would be frankly an exaggeration.
But there's no harm in keeping your eyes open.
We can walk on the wall with super-glue.
With super-powered glue, you can overcome gravity and walk on the wall like Spider-Man.
This goal has been set by several American research centers, and a group of four institutions is close to finding a solution.
With a mere two-and-a-half square centimeters of glue, the researchers were able to attach a 100-pound body to a vertical wall and hold it there.
THE American journal Science published the findings of some researchers at the University of Dayton, the University of Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology, and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the team was the result of a further development of special materials with a pre-existing structure, known as carbon nanotubes.
"We need to think of the glue as a package of spaghetti-like glue", says Zhong Lin Wang, a researcher at the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The researchers drew on the gecko's microscopic folded legs, which provide perfect grip.
Tests with materials such as glass, teflon, and sandpaper confirmed that the new glue is ten times more effective than the feet of these reptiles, while "peeling off the walls", explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's engineering department.
"This material may be useful as a temporary glue", adds Liming Dai.
Could we walk on the wall, just like Spider-Man? Maybe we can, but researchers are thinking about a less impressive use of it than connecting electronic devices, because carbon nanotubes are very conductive of heat and electricity.
It can find further application in the field of space exploration.
The superheroes can wait.
MACHINE RESEARCH - The University of California, Berkeley, is also experimenting with a new glue.
According to an article in the Journal of the American Chemical Society, scientists in California have demonstrated a glue made of a hairlike, microfilament material that self-cleans as it moves across a surface, always providing perfect adhesion.
