You have to be careful with grapefruit, orange and apple.
These high-vitamin soft drinks, especially popular in the summer, when ingested with certain life-saving medicines, alter their absorption, increasing or decreasing their effects, depending on the case, and can have serious health consequences.
The risks of combining canned or fresh fruit juices with certain medications were highlighted by David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, who announced at the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia that a glass of grapefruit, orange, or apple could reduce the absorption of certain life-saving medications, preventing their beneficial effects and endangering the patient's health.
Grapefruit juice has been used in the past by the defendants when it was found to increase the effects of certain antibiotics, antihistamines, anxiolytics, pacemakers and neurotrophs to levels considered toxic.
COMPLETE RISKS - Two years ago, the Italian Institute of Pharmacy itself published the news in its official bulletin, warning doctors and patients to take the risks of such concomitant use seriously and to be careful about what they drink when taking medicines such as Diazepam or Methadone.
NO GRAPEFRUIT - Researchers say that oranges and apples also contain substances that inhibit the effectiveness of medicines.
A long list of active substances that are inhibited by grapefruit and other fruit juices is available.
Michele Carruba, professor of the Department of Pharmacy at the State University of Milan, points out: "Such discoveries are usually immediately reported to the various national and international pharmaceutical institutes, which, if necessary, arrange for changes to be made to the information contained in the package leaflet.
Therefore, always read the package insert of the medicine you are going to buy, and if you do not understand something, do not let it influence you, but ask your doctor or pharmacist", emphasizes the expert of the Ansa Institute.
Paul Krugman has been awarded the Nobel Prize in Economics.
Paul Krugman, an American economist, won the Nobel Prize in economics for his analysis of the spatial relationships between trade patterns and economic activity.
Krugman, 55, a neo-Keynesian, teaches at Princeton University and is a well-known publicist for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the Bush administration's most vocal critics of economic and foreign policy.
A few months after the terrorist attack in September 2001, when Enron went bankrupt, Krugman predicted in a New York Times op-ed that the latter event would have even more fatal consequences for the history of the United States than the collapse of the Twin Towers.
This prediction has been controversial, and has been challenged by economists on several occasions, but we now know that it was accurate.
"I am surprised and a little shocked at how quickly the public interest has gone beyond the scandalous collapse of Enron or Worldcom", Krugman said in late 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi, a member of the European Central Bank's executive committee, Krugman is a "very valuable economist" but also "a rather aggressive critic of the Bush administration's excessive liberalism".
Open Office, the third edition was also worth the "anti-Microsoft" package
OpenOffice.org 3.0 is an open source application suite that enhances personal productivity as a free alternative to Microsoft Office, reaching a wider range of users, from home users to office users, from freelancers to government departments.
After almost a year of work overseen by SUN Microsystems and volunteer developers, the new Open Office comes with a number of new features, including a welcome screen and a redesigned, less Spartan user interface, as well as new features such as compatibility with Apple's Mac OS X operating system and support for the new ISO-compliant ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2.
Special attention has been paid to compatibility with Office 2007, so that Open Office can open new Microsoft documents (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
There are also some interesting module-specific features, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations. This can be useful when sending files via email. Another feature supports importing PDF files into the graphics module, while maintaining the page layout.
On the same interface, you can also create "hybrid PDF" documents that combine the typical Adobe format with the table manager or word processor elements.
Sharing within applications has also undergone a number of improvements: the spreadsheet manager supports sharing workbooks but prevents overwriting each other's work. Each employee's comments are marked in a different color, which helps to make them easier to recognize during the checking phase.
Some companies are already working on making some of the OpenOffice features available on the web (on the cloud), so the final version is likely to be released in the coming weeks.
The Italian version, after being available on Mirror, has been available since Friday alongside the English version, available for download at: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html
The software package is available for Linux, in addition to the usual Windows and Mac OS operating systems.
You can also request an installation CD at home or at work.
Free is probably the biggest attraction for home use, but the Open Office suite is now trying to kick the ball in the business sector, as it can also count on a number of government and school projects.
There is also no shortage of ideal education, consultancy and service services for SMEs, which can open up new business opportunities.
Open Office consists of five basic modules: Writer, a word processor equivalent to Word; Calc, a spreadsheet manager intended to replace Excel; Impress, for PowerPoint-like presentations; Dbase, the most well-known, similar to Access database manager; and finally Draw, the graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads, but considering that we're already at 3.6 million by the time the new version comes out, that number is probably higher than expected.
