Students suffer from expensive rent, a room can cost up to 900 euros
The market for university student accommodation is not affected by the crisis.
According to a recent survey by the Sunia, the Tenants' Union, a student can pay up to 900 euros for a single room in Milan, 700 euros in Florence, 650 euros in Naples, and 600 euros in Rome.
"The phenomenon has reached such an astonishing level that, due to the high costs for families, it excludes large sections of students from the opportunity to study", explains Laura Mariani, head of the Sunia study office. "The high demand from students in these cities has distorted the market to such an extent that a general price increase has been triggered for local residents".
In most cases, real estate offers also contain a number of irregularities: unregistered contracts without a rental limit, linked leases.
Sunia argued that an exceptional measure would be necessary to maximise prices by means of a review of the taxation system.
The survey details show that in Milan, in the Brianza area, a bed costs 450 euros; the average price of a single room ranges from 650 euros (Bande Nere area) to 800 euros (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera) and can reach 900 euros (Vittoria area).
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350-400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where most students live in close proximity to the university, a bed costs €250/280 for a double bed and €370-500 for a single bed.
In Rome, in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), they charge about 600 euros for a single bed and 450 euros for a double bed.
Prices are somewhat cheaper (€550 per single room) in the vicinity of other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
In suburban areas, there are some savings: a bed costs €300 and a single room costs €450 in Prenestina, Centocelle and other similar areas.
In Naples, beds cost between 300 and 450 euros, and rooms cost between 400 and 600 euros, with the highest rates in the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, a bed costs €250/350 and a single room costs at least €350.
In smaller towns, prices are lower in absolute terms but they have a greater impact on the city budget.
In cities such as Perugia, where non-EU students are also often looking for accommodation, there is another anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is about 25-30% higher than for Italian tenants.
Goodbye old Cinema Paradiso, the cities have sacrificed the time of the old cinemas
Traditional theaters are closing in favor of multiplexes.
"A city without a cinema is a blind city, like a face without eyes".
The images, made by Giuseppe Tornatore, show what is happening in the Italian cities and in the rural areas.
The suppression of the cinema - the emergence of large, multi-screen cinemas in the suburbs and the consequent decline of single-screen cinemas in the city centres - is a process that seems inevitable and irreversible, but at the same time it has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
When places of history and memory disappear, "it is as if a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared our journey and many experiences, were gone", says the director of Cinema Paradiso. The film, which won the Academy Award and the Grand Prix at the Cannes Film Festival for Tornado 20 years ago, tells the story of a small-town movie theater, the longing for a movie experience that may have been lost forever.
The figures reported by the largest association of operators, Anec, are clear: 316 traditional cinemas have closed in the last five years. e biggest losses were recorded in cinemas in the major cities: 10 cinemas in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna, which lost 82 one-screen cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And the fact that the expansion of multiplexes is responsible for their disappearance is best demonstrated by the fact that Italy has the highest number of new multi-screen cinemas in these three regions: in the last five years, the number of cinemas has increased by 195 in Lombardy, by 81 in Tuscany and by the same amount in Emilia-Romagna.
"The number of theatres in Italy has increased in an irrational way", says Paolo Protti, president of Anec. "It's okay to build new facilities, but we also have to ensure the survival of the existing ones, because when a city cinema closes, not all the tenants are willing to move to multiplexes.
Not to mention the unfunded financial support for operators: the State's outstanding debt amounts to approximately EUR 10 million.
It is a shame, both ethically and morally, that the government does not comply with the existing laws.
The market would require EUR 16-18 million per year to maintain.'
Bologna is particularly noteworthy, being the first Italian city to address the issue of closures by means of an agreement between the municipality and Anec, in order to protect and improve the outdoor and downtown single-screen cinemas.
The provisions would include tax concessions for operators and benefits for the public to promote accessibility: spectators could enter restricted areas and park in certain parking lots at a discounted rate.
"I like this initiative", says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example, perhaps by introducing other measures.
But it's also clear that traditional cinema, in order to be able to take on the battle of multiplex dominance, needs to improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audiences are much more demanding.
Preserving the traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me, and the closure of the Supercinema in Bagheri, where I spent my childhood and adolescence, gave me the spark that eventually led me to make Cinema Paradiso, even though I had been thinking about it for 10 years.
I've been living in Rome for 25 years, so when I go to the Via Nazionale, to the closed Rialto or the Quirinale, so I don't see the posters blackened by dust, I turn my head.
