The energy comes from the waves, and now the big ones are coming.
An inexhaustible source of energy that covers 70 percent of the planet's surface and is just being discovered by the big international energy companies
Waves, tides, tides, all renewable energy sources that have been the eyes of giants like Chevron, who are now trying to get their hands on it.
For over a century, research has been exploring the possibility of extracting energy from the movement of the sea, and in the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, research intensified.
The idea of using offshore energy was abandoned around 1980 when the price of oil fell, but today the demands of environmental protection and the renewed rise in the price of oil give the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be met by installations that harness the tides of the seas.
That's twice as much as what nuclear power plants are currently producing.
And then there'd be the currents and the tides.
The giants are in a frenzy.
Enersis was the first company to commit to offshore energy and signed an agreement in 2005 for a power plant to be built in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolutionary move when the signing was announced.
Two years have passed, and more and more companies are starting to speak out for offshore energy, including some that have been committed supporters of conventional energy.
"Chevron is studying technologies that harness the energy of the oceans and is considering working with us", a spokesman for one of the oil giant's subsidiaries told the Wall Street Journal.
The cooperation in question concerns the issue of obtaining the permits required by the US Energy Commission for the start-up of the offshore power project in Alaska.
This is not insignificant, especially considering that the United States is currently drilling for oil in Alaska, and President Bush has recently launched a plan to drill further.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are also pursuing offshore energy, and the amounts invested so far, as far as details are known, are evidence of growing interest.
The technology is waiting to be developed.
Experts say that this is still a very early technology, partly because the environmental impact of energy from the sea is not being addressed.
The existing facilities, such as those in Portugal or Scotland, are all small and therefore do not pose too much of an ecosystem problem.
However, to produce energy on a larger scale, facilities with a greater environmental impact are needed.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses an interconnected buoy system.
The thrust of the waves that move the buoys up and down is converted into hydraulic pressure by the plugs and cylinders inside.
The pressure turns a turbine, which feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to land by cables that run under the sea.
There are currently four similar facilities in the planning stages, pending federal approval, and some of the energy generated would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started to generate power for a shopping mall and a parking lot with six underwater turbines in the East River estuary of New York.
When the current is moving, the water moves the turbines' blades, and this rotational motion feeds the generator.
Verdant stated that it has a long list of partners waiting only for the necessary permits to use the energy.
Waves after waves.
At present, there is a need to pay special attention to the opportunities that can be exploited by the tidal wave.
Although a periodic phenomenon, tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and thus are a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine, Alaska, and other coastal states spent $7.5 million in 2008 to harness the tidal power, and that's projected to grow to $35 million by 2009.
